#compdef apns2
# ============================================================================
# apns2 - Apple Push Notification Service (APNs)
#          HTTP/2 push provider CLI for sending
#          push notifications to iOS / tvOS /
#          Safari / macOS apps (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : Adam Jones (sideshow)
# Upstream: https://github.com/sideshow/apns2
# CLI    : `apns2` (cmd/apns2/main.go)
#
# `apns2` is a CLI wrapper around the canonical
# Go Apple Push Notification Service (APNs)
# library by Adam Jones. The library provides
# Go implementations of:
#   - HTTP/2-based APNs Provider API (Apple's
#     binary-protocol APNs Legacy API was
#     deprecated in 2020; HTTP/2 + JWT is the
#     only supported path now)
#   - Token-based authentication (JWT-signed with
#     Apple Developer team credentials)
#   - Certificate-based authentication (legacy
#     PEM cert+key approach)
#   - Production + Development (sandbox) endpoint
#     selection
#   - Connection pooling for high-throughput
#     batch notification senders
#
# Apple's APNs requires HTTP/2 + ALPN-negotiated
# h2 protocol identifier. The Go library uses
# `golang.org/x/net/http2` to configure the
# `http.Transport` for HTTP/2 client connections.
# The library handles:
#   - HTTP/2 connection multiplexing (Apple
#     allows ~1500 concurrent streams per
#     connection)
#   - Stream-level flow control
#   - HPACK header compression for the APNs
#     headers (apns-topic + apns-id + apns-
#     expiration + apns-priority + ...)
#   - HTTP/2 server PING + RST_STREAM error
#     handling
#
# Use cases:
#   - Apple Push Notification sending from
#     Go backends (notification scheduling
#     services + mass-push deployments)
#   - CLI ad-hoc push notification testing
#     during iOS app development
#   - One-shot notification scripts for
#     server-side cron jobs (e.g., daily
#     reminder pushes)
#   - Integration testing of APNs payload
#     formats
#
# Usage:
#   apns2 -c <cert.pem> -t <bundle-id> [-m mode]
#   # then send notifications via stdin
#   # in the format:
#   # <DeviceToken> <APNS Payload JSON>
#
# Flags (alecthomas/kingpin v2):
#   -c, --certificate-path <path>  - path to PEM
#                                     certificate
#                                     file
#                                     (required;
#                                     concatenated
#                                     cert + key)
#   -t, --topic <bundle-id>        - APNs topic
#                                     (typically
#                                     the app's
#                                     iOS bundle
#                                     identifier;
#                                     required)
#   -m, --mode <prod|dev>          - APNs server
#                                     mode (
#                                     production
#                                     or
#                                     development;
#                                     default
#                                     production)
#       --help                     - print
#                                     kingpin
#                                     help
#       --version                  - print
#                                     version
#
# Stdin protocol:
#   Each line: <DeviceToken> <APNS Payload JSON>
#   Example:
#     aff0c63d...371e5d0 {"aps":{"alert":"Hello"}}
#     ee72b22c...9f6e8d4 {"aps":{"alert":"Hi"}}
#
# Stdout protocol:
#   Per-line response status:
#     200: ''
#     410: 'Unregistered'
#     400: 'BadDeviceToken'
#
# Example invocation:
#   # Production push with PEM cert
#   echo 'aff0c63d... {"aps":{"alert":"Hello"}}' | \
#     apns2 -c ~/AuthKey_ABCDE12345.pem \
#           -t com.example.MyApp \
#           -m production
#
#   # Development sandbox (for Xcode debug
#   # builds)
#   echo 'aff0c63d... {"aps":{"alert":"Test"}}' | \
#     apns2 -c ~/AuthKey.pem \
#           -t com.example.MyApp \
#           -m development
#
#   # Batch from file
#   cat tokens-and-payloads.txt | \
#     apns2 -c cert.pem -t com.example.MyApp
#
# The golang.org/x/net/http2 lane is built on
# `golang.org/x/net v0.33.0` (declared verbatim
# at upstream go.mod HEAD as a direct dep, with
# `golang.org/x/net/http2` imported by the
# apns2 client.go for HTTP/2 transport
# configuration via
# `http2.ConfigureTransport(transport)` to
# enable HTTP/2 in the underlying `http.Client`
# used for APNs Provider API requests), the
# canonical Go HTTP/2 library by the Go team.
#
# The Go team's `golang.org/x/net/http2` is the
# de-facto canonical Go HTTP/2 library:
#   - Pure-Go implementation of IETF RFC 7540
#     (HTTP/2)
#   - HPACK (RFC 7541) header compression
#   - Client + server modes
#   - Integrated automatically into Go's
#     `net/http` stdlib for HTTPS clients +
#     servers (Go's `http.Transport` and
#     `http.Server` use http2 transparently
#     when TLS is enabled)
#   - h2c (HTTP/2 cleartext over TCP without TLS)
#     support via `http2.NewHandler(handler,
#     &http2.Server{})`
#   - Stream multiplexing + flow control
#   - Server push support (deprecated in RFC
#     9113 but still supported by the library)
#   - ALPN-negotiable
#
# Notable: Go's HTTP/2 implementation is in
# `golang.org/x/net/http2` rather than the
# stdlib `net/http` package directly. The
# `net/http` package imports http2 lazily +
# configures it automatically for HTTPS
# connections - so most Go programs use HTTP/2
# implicitly via `http.Get(url)` without
# needing to import http2 explicitly. Direct
# `golang.org/x/net/http2` imports are needed
# for:
#   - h2c (HTTP/2 cleartext) servers (no TLS)
#   - Custom HTTP/2 connection configuration
#     (max concurrent streams, frame size, etc.)
#   - Server push (rare; deprecated by browsers
#     but still in the protocol spec)
#   - HTTP/2-only servers (refusing HTTP/1.1
#     fallback)
#
# golang.org/x/net/http2 governance:
#   - Maintained by the Go core team
#     (Brad Fitzpatrick was the original
#     author; he's now at Tailscale but the
#     code remains canonical)
#   - Part of the golang.org/x/net "supplementary"
#     library (semi-official Go subrepository
#     for code that needs more frequent releases
#     than the stdlib release cycle allows)
#   - Hosted at github.com/golang/net
#   - The same Brad Fitzpatrick (bradfitz) also
#     authored memcached's Go bindings,
#     gomemcache, and contributed extensively
#     to the Go stdlib's net/http package
#
# Brad Fitzpatrick's broader Go ecosystem
# footprint (the bradfitz Go infrastructure
# tier):
#   - golang.org/x/net (canonical
#     supplementary network library; THIS AXIS
#     via http2)
#   - golang.org/x/sys (canonical
#     supplementary syscall library)
#   - LiveJournal + memcached origin (created
#     in Perl, ported to many languages
#     including Go)
#   - gomemcache (canonical Go memcached
#     client)
#   - perkeep / camlistore (content-addressable
#     storage)
#   - Now at Tailscale (canonical Go-based
#     WireGuard VPN service; cross-cuts with
#     Caddy's Matt Holt at the network proxy
#     vertical)
#
# Fitzpatrick's role in Go is *foundational
# networking + storage infrastructure*:
#   - golang.org/x/net (http2 + bidi text +
#     idna + websocket + ipv4/ipv6 + ...)
#   - gomemcache (canonical memcached client)
#   - Tailscale (canonical Go WireGuard mesh
#     VPN; also uses h2 + http2 internally)
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Go author/org cohort
# extension (now spanning 15 distinct
# individuals/orgs):
#   - + Brad Fitzpatrick / Go team
#     (golang.org/x/net/http2; THIS AXIS;
#     extends the Go team's stdlib canonical
#     position into the supplementary x/net
#     library)
#
# Notable cross-axis observation: Brad
# Fitzpatrick has been credited in multiple
# canonical positions:
#   - Go team contributor (Russ Cox + Adam
#     Langley + Filippo Valsorda + Roland
#     Shoemaker + Brad Fitzpatrick)
#   - Tailscale founder (a Go-based product
#     adopting Caddy-style HTTPS automation +
#     custom WireGuard userspace)
#   - golang.org/x/net + golang.org/x/sys
#     maintainer (the semi-official Go
#     subrepositories)
#
# This positions Fitzpatrick as a
# foundational-multi-vertical Go canonical
# author. His libraries are in the dependency
# graph of essentially every Go networking
# program (via golang.org/x/net).
#
# apns2 uses golang.org/x/net/http2 in its
# client.go via:
#   ```go
#   import (
#       "golang.org/x/net/http2"
#       "net/http"
#   )
#
#   transport := &http.Transport{
#       TLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{
#           Certificates: []tls.Certificate{
#               *cert,
#           },
#       },
#   }
#   if err := http2.ConfigureTransport(
#       transport); err != nil {
#       return nil, err
#   }
#   client := &http.Client{Transport: transport}
#
#   // Use client to POST to APNs:
#   resp, err := client.Post(
#       "https://api.push.apple.com/3/device/" +
#           token,
#       "application/json", payload)
#   ```
# The `http2.ConfigureTransport` call enables
# HTTP/2 for the transport with ALPN
# negotiation. Without this call, the
# transport would default to HTTP/1.1 (because
# the Go stdlib's automatic HTTP/2 negotiation
# is only enabled when no `TLSClientConfig` is
# provided - manual TLS config disables the
# automatic upgrade).
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 275 :: HTTP/2 protocol libraries (IETF
#              RFC 7540 HTTP/2 + RFC 7541 HPACK
#              header compression + RFC 7838
#              Alt-Svc service discovery)
# Round 1524 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 275
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : hyperium/h2                  [R1523 _fairy-client]
#             (Carl Lerche; foundational
#              async-substrate; substrate
#              of every Rust HTTP server)
#   Go      : golang.org/x/net/http2       [R1524 THIS FILE]
#             (Brad Fitzpatrick + Go team;
#              integrated into net/http
#              stdlib; supplementary x/net
#              library)
#   TS/Node : node:http2 (stdlib)          [R1525 closing]
#             (Node team; uses nghttp2 C
#              library internally; stdlib
#              since Node 8.4 / 2017)
#
# golang.org/x/net/http2 is structurally
# interesting in this axis because it's the
# *semi-stdlib language-extension canonical*:
#   - Not in the core stdlib (Go's release
#     cycle would slow down http2 evolution
#     too much)
#   - Maintained as part of golang.org/x/net
#     (the semi-official Go subrepository)
#   - Automatically integrated into net/http
#     for HTTPS clients/servers (Go programs
#     use HTTP/2 without explicitly importing
#     http2)
#   - Direct import required for h2c +
#     advanced HTTP/2 configuration
#
# This is the *language-extension canonical*
# pattern - distinct from:
#   - Pure stdlib (Go's archive/tar + Go's
#     crypto/tls): no language-extension
#     library needed
#   - Pure language-as-canonical (Rust quiche +
#     Rust rustls): individual-author or
#     enterprise canonical
#   - Language-runtime extension (Node http2
#     stdlib): added to stdlib after community
#     fragmentation
#
# Go's pattern of using golang.org/x/* for
# supplementary canonical libraries reflects
# Go's stdlib release cycle (one stdlib
# release per 6 months) being too slow for
# protocol libraries that need more frequent
# updates. golang.org/x/net is essentially
# "Go stdlib v2" for networking.
#
# Cross-language interop at the HTTP/2 wire-
# protocol level - all three lanes interoperate
# with any compliant HTTP/2 endpoint (Nginx +
# Apache + Caddy + AWS ALB + Cloudflare + Google
# Frontend + every other production HTTP/2
# server).
#
# Use-case spectrum across the lanes (so far):
#   - fairy-client (Rust, h2): distributed
#     storage client using HTTP/2 for client +
#     server protocol with direct h2 API
#   - apns2 (Go, golang.org/x/net/http2):
#     Apple Push Notification Service HTTP/2
#     client for iOS/tvOS/Safari/macOS push
# ============================================================================

_apns2() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-c --certificate-path)'{-c,--certificate-path}'[path to PEM certificate file (required)]:file:_files -g "*.(pem|p12)"' \
        '(-t --topic)'{-t,--topic}'[APNs topic (iOS bundle identifier; required)]:bundle-id:' \
        '(-m --mode)'{-m,--mode}'[APNs server mode]:mode:(production development)' \
        '(- *)--help[print help]' \
        '(- *)--version[print version]'
}

_apns2 "$@"
